@node Switching to telega
@section Switching to telega

@findex telega-extras-switch-to
The command @code{telega-extras-switch-to} provides an intelligent way to navigate the various @samp{telega} buffers with a single key binding. Its behavior depends on the current context:

@itemize
@item
If no @samp{telega} buffer exists, it starts @samp{telega}.
@item
If a @samp{telega} buffer exists but is not the current buffer, it switches to it.
@item
If the current buffer is a chat buffer and point is not at the end, it moves point to the end (to see the latest messages). If point is already at the end, it kills the chat buffer and returns to the root buffer.
@item
If the current buffer is the root buffer showing the archive, repeated invocations move point to the top and then reset the filter back to the main view.
@item
If the current buffer is the root buffer showing the main view, it moves point to the top.
@end itemize

This cycling behavior means a single key binding is sufficient for all common navigation between @samp{telega} buffers.

@node Smart enter
@section Smart enter

@findex telega-extras-smart-enter
The command @code{telega-extras-smart-enter} performs a context-dependent action in a @samp{telega} chat buffer. If point is on a URL, it opens the URL with @code{browse-url-at-point}. If point is on a button, it activates the button with @code{push-button}. Otherwise, it sends the content of the input area as a message via @code{telega-chatbuf-input-send}. This provides a unified ``do the right thing'' key binding for the most common actions in a chat buffer.

@node Viewing archive and main chat lists
@section Viewing archive and main chat lists

@findex telega-extras-view-archive
@findex telega-extras-view-main
The command @code{telega-extras-view-archive} resets the active filters in the @samp{telega} root buffer and applies the @samp{archive} filter, showing only archived chats. The command @code{telega-extras-view-main} does the same but applies the @samp{main} filter, restoring the default view. These commands provide direct access to the two primary chat lists without navigating through @samp{telega}'s filter interface.

@node Org capture integration
@section Org capture integration

@findex telega-extras-chat-org-capture
The command @code{telega-extras-chat-org-capture} captures the Telegram message at point into an Org mode note. It first stores an Org link to the message with @code{org-store-link} and then invokes @code{org-capture} with the @samp{"n"} template key. This assumes you have an Org capture template bound to @samp{"n"} that is configured to use the stored link. The command is useful for saving important messages or action items from conversations into your Org workflow.

@node Sending files from Dired
@section Sending files from Dired

@findex telega-extras-dired-attach-send
When you have files marked in a Dired buffer that you want to send via Telegram, the command @code{telega-extras-dired-attach-send} handles the entire process. It retrieves the marked files, prompts you to select a destination chat, and attaches each file using the appropriate @samp{telega} attachment function based on the file extension: audio files (@samp{.mp3}, @samp{.flac}) are attached as audio, video files (@samp{.mp4}, @samp{.mkv}) as video, images as photos, and everything else as generic files.

@findex telega-extras-chatbuf-attach-most-recent-file
The command @code{telega-extras-chatbuf-attach-most-recent-file} is a convenience for the common case of wanting to send the most recently downloaded file. It finds the newest file in the downloads directory (specified by @code{paths-dir-downloads}, using @code{files-extras-newest-file} from @samp{files-extras.el}) and attaches it to the current chat buffer. If the downloads directory is empty, it signals an error.

@node Downloading attachments
@section Downloading attachments

@findex telega-extras-download-file
The command @code{telega-extras-download-file} downloads the file attachment from the message at point (or from an optionally provided MESSAGE argument) using @code{telega-msg-save}. This provides a quick way to save an attachment without navigating through @samp{telega}'s menu system.

@node Audio transcription
@section Audio transcription

@findex telega-extras-transcribe-audio
The command @code{telega-extras-transcribe-audio} initiates speech recognition for a voice note message. It checks that the message at point (or the provided MESSAGE argument) is indeed a voice note, then calls the internal @code{telega--recognizeSpeech} function to request transcription from Telegram's servers.

If @code{telega-extras-auto-share-audio-transcript} is non-@code{nil} and the message was sent by the current user, the command also sets up a polling mechanism that checks every 5 seconds (for up to 60 seconds) whether the transcript has become available. Once ready, the transcript is automatically posted as a reply to the original voice note (@ref{Auto-sharing audio transcripts}).

@node Chat and topic navigation
@section Chat and topic navigation

@findex telega-extras-menu
The command @code{telega-extras-menu} displays a transient menu for quickly opening predefined chats and topics. The menu entries are derived from the @code{telega-extras-chats} user option (@ref{Chat configuration}). Selecting an item calls @code{telega-extras-open-chat}, which starts @samp{telega} if needed, navigates to the specified chat, and optionally opens a topic thread within it.

